{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f8d7017e-4500-4359-8a67-9adfd30422de","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports constructor injection for `TestContext` (added in 3.3+). Here's the modern pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Constructor handles sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init via [TestInitialize]\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup here (runs before each test)\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        TestContext.WriteLine(\"works!\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** replaces the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property-setter pattern.\n- Put **sync init** in the constructor, **async init** in a `[TestInitialize]` method returning `async Task`.\n- For **one-time class-level** async init, use `[ClassInitialize]` on a `static async Task` method.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5e6ba087-c9c7-48d6-8ff1-611c9ce54433","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. Let me check what MSTest 3.x recommends for TestContext injection and initialization.\n\nIn MSTest v3 (3.3+), the recommended approach changed:\n- `TestContext` is now injected via constructor instead of the old property setter pattern\n- `ClassInitialize` and `ClassCleanup` are still attribute-based static methods\n- For async init, you can use `[TestInitialize]` with async Task return\n\nLet me give them the modern MSTest v3 guidance.\n\nKey points for MSTest 3.x:\n\n\n- Constructor injection is the preferred way to get TestContext, though the property pattern still works for backward compatibility\n- You can initialize state synchronously in the constructor or use `[TestInitialize]` for per-test setup\n- For async initialization, `[TestInitialize]` with an async Task return type is the way to go\n\nSetting up the example...","outputTokens":669,"requestId":"9820:24F978:10F5A28:1535676:69FFE0C1"},"id":"7e96042c-a5f2-4204-aa35-99f950433187","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:35:10.604Z","parentId":"3a7d4467-90ed-43d8-8927-bd9aab3f2eae"}
